metadata.name: GEN XYZ Das Occult #7894
metadata.description:
A 10k Generative Profile Pic collection
GEN XYZ Das Occult - by culla - @tamccullough

move over cryptopunks
there is a new group on the scene

100% code - not an image composition

A bunch of common palettes
A selection of rare palettes
And a smaller set of ultra rare palettes
However, rarity will be based on what combinations the code produces

The majority of tokens will not have a special trait
However your token might have one or even multiple special traits
But, be aware that only the last special trait added will be listed in the features

Even then, look closely, because not all aspects of the canvas are included in the features. Collectors should still look closely and choose what they like when buying on secondary.

Which team are you on? X or O?

follow culla on twitter for updates. Or maybe __acolyte__

If the non reserved tokens mint out quickly, Access List mints will have 24 hours to mint reserves assigned to those wallets

Thank you for supporting an emerging artist in the generative art space

Access List reserves were given to holders of the following PFP collections created by culla
2x for each Basqunk held
1x for each Inkspunk, TwoFourQunk, V0iD, DeeManz, Punkasso and CR0$$KULL
You would have needed to transfer the above tokens to your mint wallet at the time of the snapshot

share your tokens on social media with #genxyznft
Made with love by culla using p5.js

metadata.name: Ghost Friend #32
metadata.description:
Everyone dreams of a friend that would never leave them (we prefer to call it "haunting" around here), that could follow you around no matter where you go (even if it involves going through brick walls) while also being able to scare away their toughest enemies - and trust me, there's no better option than a ghost friend!

Each ghost is created exclusively with code (mostly in p5.js) without any assets and has a unique yet universally charming appearance 👻

Credit for visual inspiration goes to spooky project by watabo_shi, as well as ghostly artworks by Jordan Jenkins, Jonas Mosesson, Rytis, amy luo, Marvin Rudolph and others.

License: CC-BY-SA 4.0

metadata.name: IMAGINARY NEW YORK IN UKIYO-E #92
metadata.description:
In the late 19th century, the style of ukiyo-e was brought to the West and had a major impact on the techniques of Western painting.
Van Gogh, Monet, and other up-and-coming painters of the time were inspired by the Far Eastern Japan seen through Ukiyo-e and painted.
At that time, the great distance, which was a physical barrier, stirred the imagination.

Time has changed, and in the 21st century, I do not paint. I do not even use my imagination. I simply type the words "Ukiyo-e style New York while being in Japan, with a computer in hand, accessing a server in the United States.
It is as if a painter in the U.S. had been thinking of Japan in the Far East and painted a picture.

But still, what came out of it was certainly a work of art created by my own hands.

Imagination is a unique act.
Imagination is free.
Imagination does not belong to anyone.

What is imagination?


19世紀後半、浮世絵というスタイルが西洋にもたらされ、西洋絵画の手法に大きなインパクトを与えた。
ゴッホ、モネ、当時の新進気鋭の画家たちは、浮世絵から見る極東の日本に思いを馳せ、絵を描いた。
当時は距離という大きな隔たりが想像力を掻き立てた。

時は変わって21世紀、私は絵を描かない。想像力も働かせない。「浮世絵スタイルのニューヨーク」と単に文字を書くだけだ。日本にいながらコンピュータを片手にアメリカにあるサーバーにアクセスしながら。
それにもかかわらず、ニューヨークにいる人工知能が極東の日本に思いを馳せ描いたような絵が生成される。

だが依然として、そこから生まれたのは確かに私の手によって生み出された想像的なニューヨークの姿である。

想像は自由なのだ。
想像は誰のものでもない。

想像とは。

metadata.name: 🔸WOMAN 🔹LIFE🔹 FREEDOM🔸 #1141
metadata.description:
📅 To be recorded in history as the first event-based stamp collection of generative art on the blockchain. 

🟩🟩🟩🟩🟩
⬜️⬜️⬜️⬜️⬜️
🟥🟥🟥🟥🟥

🔆The people of my country – Iran - have been chanting three words for several days: 🔸Woman🔸🔹Life🔸🔸Freedom🔸.

🟢For over forty years, we have fought for these beautiful words. Today, our most basic human rights are being ignored in Iran, and we fight for them every day. In my land, women fight and die but do not accept humiliation. Women and men stand shoulder to shoulder and fight together.

🟢I published this collection of 1401 generative tokens to show my support for the people of Iran. 401 tokens are reserved for other known supporters of this cause, and 1000 tokens are free to mint.

🟢All my works about Iran's freedom are royalty-free and will always be. Due to fxhash's limitation on royalty selection, I have selected it all for the minter.

metadata.name: Generative Fantasies: 101 Compositions #48
metadata.description:
This could be a follow-up to Herbert W. Franke's finding of interesting connections between Constructivism and Generative art, where at first, technological limits allowed only simple line drawings, based on fixed proportions, and later were extended by the use of random generators. Constructivism, as an art movement, sought to depict modern civilization, the symbiotic relationship between technology and art, industrialization, and urban spaces. Iakov Chernikhov (Яков Чернихов), an architect and graphic artist, was one of the influential figures in Constructivism. He extensively used the two-point perspective with an observation point below the ground in his drawings. 

In this (my) exploration of two-point perspective, random, colorful, and glassy constructions visual resemblance to Chernikhov’s oeuvre is inescapable. Therefore the title is a play on the original title of his book Architectural Fantasies: 101 Compositions in Color, 101 Architectural Miniatures from 1933.

The subtle grain effect is done with p5.grain library by Gorilla Sun (@gorillasu) & meezwhite (@meezwhite). 

Look out for the FOMO keyboard key to unlock more variations.

metadata.name: 70s Tapestry #37
metadata.description:
70s Tapestry is a tribute to the fine art work of embroiderers, and the 70s design.

Variations include :

- 10 Color Palettes
- Dark or Light background
- A reversed color mode
- 1 or 2 palettes used
- 4 types of framing, including a randomized one
- 3 types of embroidery tile type distribution
- and some special rare traits

metadata.name: SuperCube 1000 #652
metadata.description:
Celebrating 1000 projects on fxhash by releasing 1000 unique editions for free.

This is a tribute to Victor Vasarely (1906-1997), whom I consider to be one of the fathers of the generative art movement, and whose art was very present in the house I grew up in as a child.
